<font color="#FF0000">REURNING HOME</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar 25 22:49:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Julia,<br>
     In regards to my own return home and the returns of my most men in New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania area (many of which belong to our Veteran conference), our return trip was differernt than is portrayed.  Some men in other parts of the country returned home to protests and hostilities.  I am here to tell you that at least in the aforemention areas, most guys did not return home to jeering crowds, insults or attacks.<br>
     The biggest problem in my opinion that Nam vets faced was the short return time.  It took me four days for processing from Vietnam to my discharge in the United States.  I never properly said Good Bye to my friends (even missed a few), never got to talk about what we went through.  The World War Vet had weeks aboard transport ships to put a sort of finality to their service and had their friends with them to talk to about their experiences.<br>
     One thing you have to understand about the United States during Vietnam was that since it was a undeclared war, without a total effort, it didn't effect the lives of most Americans.  Unless someone had a loved one serve, their interest in Vietnam was minor.  Life among people in the States went on and things changed, while life for a vet was like a frozen period in a guy's life.  When many of us got back, you would ddiscover how old friends had different attitudes and how your own attitiude had changed because of your service.  I came home to find that I no longer had a lot in common with old friends, unless they had served.<br>
     In places like New York City, you wouldn't find much verbal abuse from protestors, because the blue collar, middle class citizens of the various neighborhoods (like the one I grew up in) usually wouldn't stand for anti-war protests.  If you went to Whitehall street in downtown Manhatten, where processing for draftees occured, you would find protestors and people who supported Gov't and the soldiers shouting at each other.  I've seen fistfights occur between the two groups.<br>
    Where I lived, the most dangerous feelings you received was the indifference of most people.  Once out of the service, most people would ignore the Nam Vet.  They didn't want to hear about what happened.  We were never allowed to express our feelings or talk about our experiences.  This is what hurt many guys the most.  People never avoided me, they just didn't want to hear about what really happened.  Even my local Veterans of Foreign Wars unit, made of mostly World War II vets didn't really want Nam Vets.  I was lucky to have a wife and family that wanted me to talk it out, some guys were less fortunate.  Many Nam vets had trouble finding jobs when we first got back.  Unemployment would pay you less than someone who never went, because you made a less than average salary in the military.  It took time, but most Nam vets I know are stable, well employed decent guys.  I never knew many guys that killed themselves either. There is a posting on here from a guy who sent me articles on suicide from the Center from Disease Control.  It seems that suicide numbers are actually now about 15,000 to 20,000 guys and I believe it.  The fact many of us did well in a society that was indifferent and wanted to forget is a testament to the strength of Nam Vets everywhere to overcome.  I hope some of this helps you.     
<p><code>--   (Charlie) </code><p>


